exports[`renderers (snapshot) > cost-only.json → markdown 1`] = `
"# pg-explain report

> **Verdict:** 1 warning. Cost-only plan (no timing).

## Summary

| Metric | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Mode | cost-only (no ANALYZE) |
| Findings | 0 critical, 1 warning(s), 0 note(s) |

## Plan tree

\`\`\`
Seq Scan on events  —  rows≈250,000 est
\`\`\`

## Findings

### 🟠 Warning — Sequential scan on events (250,000 est. rows)

\`PGX_SEQ_SCAN_LARGE\`

**What:** Postgres read events sequentially, scanning roughly 250,000 rows (estimated — run with ANALYZE for actuals).

**Why:** A row filter ((created_at > now())) is applied after reading every row, so no index narrowed the scan.

**Fix:** Add an index covering the WHERE/JOIN predicate on events so Postgres can skip non-matching rows. If the query genuinely needs most of the table, the seq scan is correct — reduce the rows touched instead.

- Identify the selective columns in the WHERE/JOIN predicate.
- Ensure they are sargable (no function-wrapping or implicit casts on the column).
- If selectivity is low, a partial index (WHERE …) may be better.

_Index the predicate columns:_
\`\`\`sql
CREATE INDEX ON events (<predicate columns>) -- columns from the filter above;
\`\`\`

📖 [PostgreSQL docs](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/indexes-intro.html)
"
`;

