"# pg-explain report

> **Verdict:** 2 notes — top cost: Index Only Scan using events_created_at_idx on events (15% of time). Total 12.0 ms.

## Summary

| Metric | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Planning time | 0.600 ms |
| Execution time | 12.0 ms |
| Findings | 0 critical, 0 warning(s), 2 note(s) |

## Plan tree

\`\`\`
Aggregate  —  rows=1 · self 0.600 ms (5%)
└─ Index Only Scan using events_created_at_idx on events  —  rows=42 (est 1,200,000, 28571× over) · self 1.8 ms (15%)
\`\`\`

## Bottlenecks (by self time)

| # | Node | Self time | % of total | Rows |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Index Only Scan using events_created_at_idx on events | 1.8 ms | 15.0% | 42 |
| 2 | Aggregate | 0.600 ms | 5.0% | 1 |

## Findings

### 🔵 Note — 28,571x row overestimate on events

\`PGX_ROW_MISESTIMATE\`

**What:** Postgres estimated 1,200,000 rows but 42 were produced — a 28,571x overestimate on events.

**Why:** The planner's row estimate is based on statistics that are stale, missing, or too coarse for this predicate (e.g. correlated columns the planner treats as independent).

**Fix:** Refresh and sharpen statistics for events: run ANALYZE events, raise per-column statistics targets on the predicate columns, and add extended statistics for correlated columns so the planner estimates rows correctly.

- Refresh table statistics first; this alone often fixes the estimate.
- If the column has a skewed/uneven distribution, raise its statistics target and re-ANALYZE.
- If the predicate spans multiple correlated columns, create extended statistics so the planner stops assuming independence.

_Refresh statistics:_
\`\`\`sql
ANALYZE events;
\`\`\`

_Raise per-column statistics target:_
\`\`\`sql
ALTER TABLE events ALTER COLUMN <column> SET STATISTICS 1000;
ANALYZE events;
\`\`\`

_Add extended statistics for correlated columns:_
\`\`\`sql
CREATE STATISTICS <stats_name> (dependencies, ndistinct) ON <col_a>, <col_b> FROM events;
ANALYZE events;
\`\`\`

📖 [PostgreSQL docs](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/planner-stats.html)

### 🔵 Note — JIT compilation took 9.5 ms (79.2% of execution)

\`PGX_SIGNIFICANT_JIT\`

**What:** JIT spent 9.5 ms generating, optimizing, and emitting machine code, out of 12.0 ms total execution time. The compilation overhead outweighs the runtime it saved.

**Why:** The plan's estimated cost crossed jit_above_cost, so Postgres JIT-compiled the query — but the query is too short for compilation to pay off, often because a row overestimate inflated the cost.

**Fix:** Raise jit_above_cost (and jit_inline_above_cost / jit_optimize_above_cost) so short queries skip JIT, or disable JIT for this session with SET jit = off. Then investigate why the cost estimate is high enough to trigger JIT — frequently a row overestimate fixable with ANALYZE.

- Confirm the query is consistently short-running before tuning — JIT pays off on long, CPU-bound queries.
- Raise jit_above_cost above this plan's total cost so similar queries skip JIT entirely.
- If only inlining/optimization are expensive, raise jit_inline_above_cost / jit_optimize_above_cost instead of disabling JIT.
- Check the planner's row estimates against actuals — an overestimate that inflates cost is the usual reason a cheap query triggers JIT; run ANALYZE on the relations involved.

_Disable JIT for this session:_
\`\`\`sql
SET jit = off;
\`\`\`

_Raise the JIT cost thresholds:_
\`\`\`sql
SET jit_above_cost = <above this plan's total cost>;
SET jit_inline_above_cost = <higher>;
SET jit_optimize_above_cost = <higher>;
\`\`\`

_Refresh statistics if the cost is driven by a row overestimate:_
\`\`\`sql
ANALYZE <table>;
\`\`\`

📖 [PostgreSQL docs](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/runtime-config-query.html#GUC-JIT-ABOVE-COST)
"
`;

